<h2 id="route-optimization">Rule 2: Geographic Clustering With 4-Zone Maximum</h2>

<div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
<p>Top HVAC companies never scatter techs randomly across their service area. They use geographic clustering with strict zone assignments that reduce drive time by 35-50%.</p>

<p><strong>The 4-Zone Rule:</strong> Companies serving areas larger than 20 miles diameter create maximum four zones. Each tech starts their day in one zone and completes 80% of jobs within a 15-minute radius. This approach reduces fuel costs by $180-240 monthly per tech and adds 1.5-2 billable hours daily.</p>

<p><strong>Zone Assignment Strategy:</strong> Assign techs to zones based on home location, not arbitrary boundaries. A tech living in the northwest suburbs should work northwest jobs first, not downtown appointments that require 45-minute drives.</p>

<p><strong>Cross-zone scheduling limits:</strong> Elite companies limit cross-zone appointments to 20% of daily schedules. Emergency calls justify zone crossings, but routine maintenance and service calls should stay within assigned areas.</p>
</div>

